{"/service/ndnp/deu/batch_deu_dover_ver01/data/sn85042354/00383343331/1910092401/0941.xml":{"full_text":"Postmaster Jester\nMore\nImportant improvements have been j\nmade In the mail collection service\nby Postmaster M.Howard Jester, which\nwill go Into effect on September 29.\nUnder the new order collections of\nmall will be made all over the city,\nException is made, however, in .a few\noutlying districts and on some holl\ndays, when thecollectors are given the\nday off.\nResidents beyond Washington street\nbridge and also those beyond Third\nstreet, bridge will be given Improved\nservice and Ihe change will be wel\ncorned.\nThe new changes include;\nHORNING TRIPS.\nCommencing at 5.30 a m. each morn\ning except, Sunday the letter boxes in\nthe territory bounded by Madison\nstreet on the west, and Pine street on\nthe east. Christiana creek on the south\nand Brandywine creek on the north,\nand No. 1916 Market street.\nEVENING TRIPS.\nCommencing September 29, 1910, and\nuntil further notice the letter.boxes of\nthe entire city will, with the excep\ntion of a few outlying boxes, be col\nlected from at. night commencing at\n6 and 6.30 p. in. This will include\neach night except Sunday, when the\ncollection commences at 4 p. m. and\non some of the holidays when the col\nlector\u00bb are given the day off. but upon\nsuch occasions the public is notified\nthrough Ihe papers.\nCommencing at 640 P. M.\nJefferson street on the west, and\nWalnut street on the east. Christiana\nriver bn the south, and Brandywine\ncreek on the north, except box at Mar\nket and A streets.\nMarket street, Shipley street. Second\nand French. Front and French, ami\nP., W. tt, B. depot, first floor; Delaware\navenue to Jefferson. Jefferson street to\nNinth, Ninth street to Postoftice. King\nstreet, Eighth to Front, two collec\nlions nightly, second collection com\nmenchig at 8.30 p. ra,\nCommencing at 6 l*. X.\nFrom Ninth to Brandywine creek\non the north, from Jefferson street to\ncity line on the west, except box at\nWawasset and Jackson.\nCommencing at 8 P. M.\nto city line on the\nNinth street\nI\nI\n1\n\n419\nDrs. Pierce Cann\nA NEW DISCOVERY\nMarket SL\ni\nIn Titalirod air. We can gir# thla air to\nanron\u00bb* children aa well at adults. No of\nthe heart.\nWe will mak\u00ab your old plate over and\nguarantee it not to drop. $4.00.\nfeet\nStorage\nHousehold Goods,\nGeneral Merchandise,\nAutomobiles Carriages\nCHARLES WARNER GO\nM\nGuarantee Storage Warehouse Department,\nNo. 836 Morkot St.\nToloohono 1840.\n3rd and Fronch St\u00bb.\nW. W. Bottomley\nj\n\n\nDecorations tor Buildings. Store\nFronts andPrivate Residences, for rent\nor sale. Estimalesand designs furnished.\nFlags and Flag Poles tor Sale\nS. W. Cor. 4th and Tatnall Sts.\nYou Can Save Money\nBY INQUIRING ABOUT OUR\nFactory Direct Plan\n\nI\n99\nU\nNew Sample Room, No. 90U King Street, is\nopen Wednesdays and Saturdays. Let us explain the\nplan of selling pianos from factory to home direct.\nWrite us or call by Phone.\nOur\nHarkness Piano Co\n\u20229\nWilmington, Del\nSample Room:\n904 King Street.\nOffice:\n304 W. 50th Street.\nD. 6 8. Phene 4589.\nThe Automatic Telephone\nhas become a necessity in every home and place of business\nTHE AUTOMATIC\nhas thoroughly demonstrated its superiority over the\nOLD STYLE SYSTEM\nIt is Prompt, Reliable and Absolutely Secret, with no\nparty lines nor interruptions.\nAN AUTOMATIC\nin your residence costs but Two Dollars a month; Think\nof It! Your Saving in Car Fare alone will pay for it.\nConnections with the Keystone, Philadelphia.\nWE HAVE A MUSICAL PROPOSITION\nwhich will interest you. Call or Phone and our representative\nwill Cheerfully Explain.\nWILMINGTON \u00f4 PHILA. TRACTION CO.\n603 Market Street\nPlans\nCollections of Mail\nsouth; from Jefferson street to city\nline on Ihe west, except boxes as fol\nlows: Sixth avenue and Coleman,\nSecond and Ford, and Second and Rod\nman.\nCommencing 940 1'. M.\nAll over Washington street bridge\nfrom Brandywine creek to city line\non the north, city line on the west to\nand including Market street, except\nbox at Thirty-second and Madison;\nMarket street? to city line on the east,\nBrandywine creek on the south to\nTwenty-third and Jessup, except box\nst Fourteenth and R. R. avenue; Pop\nlar street to Christiana creek on the\neast. Christiana creek on the south to\nBrandywine creek on the north, except\nbox foot of Poplar street, and Seventh\nand lyicnst. All territory over Third\nstreet bridge, except box at Newr Cas\ntle avenue and D. street.\nRepublican Comm 11 tee Meets.\nThe Republican County Committee\nis meeting this aftetnoon at the\nVoting Men's Republican Club to dis\ncuss campaign plans.\nOn a Yacht Outing.\nThe managers and the household of\nthe Y. W. C. A. and the Arrow Club\nare on an outing today on General\nT. Coleman duPonfs yacht. Tech. The\nyacht left with a large party about\n1 o'clock this afternoon. 1* will re\nturn at 10 o'clock this evening.\nThrovfn From Flying Horse.\nThrown from off the horse of a\nSeaford.\nMiss\nmerry-go-round\nRuth Stevens, the 14-year-old daugh\nter of Mr. and Mrs. Woodland Ste\nvens had her left knee broken and\nshe received bruises and lacerations\nabout the body.\nat\nMashed His ringer,\nFrank A. Baker, a machinist, of No.\nSI West Seventh street, was treated\nat the Physicians' and Surgeons' Hos\npita I for a mashed finger today,\nMr. Saulshury to Return.\nWtllard Saulshury, who has been\nabroad for several weeks will arrive\nhome this evening or tomorrow.\nINSANE MAN\nSENT INTO STATE\nTreated in Reading and Then,\nis Passed Along Into\nDelaware\nExamined by physicians at the po\nlice station to-day, who declared him\ninsane, Frank Junsuski, a foreigner. I\nbelieved to be a Pole, was to-day re\nmoved to the State Hospital for In\nsane at Farnhnrst.\nP., B. and W. rail\nHe was taken into custody\nIn the man's pockets was found a\nThe stranger made several attempts\nlast night to end his life by jumping\nin front of trolly ears on the Newport\nand Stanton line of the Wilmington\nand Philadelphia Traction Company\nat Newport, and he caused consider\nable excitement in that usually quiet\ncommunity. His attempts to kill him\nself in this way being frustrated he\nproceeded to the\nroad and threw himself across the\ntracks.\nbefore a train came along.\nthe I\nnote signed by\\Dr. M. L. Ernest, of\nSt. Joseph's Hospital. Reading. Pa,\nadd t eased to the directors of\npoor of that city. He set forth that\nthe man had no home and was sub\nject to epileptic fits and recommended\nthat he be either placed in the alms\nhouse or given transportation out of\nthe state. It. is evident that trans\nportation was provided and the man\nlanded in Wilmington.\nTHF H! SINESS OUTLOOK.\nThe weekly trade review-\u00bb think\nthe business outlook somewhat uncer\ntain, although not necessarily alarm\ningly so. Conditions must become\nmore definite before there can bo\nany significant speculative actlvtly.\nI\nDun's says:\nWith crops aggregating large in\nquantity and value. In spile of the\nreduced yield of spring wheat; with\npolities becoming so intense and un\ncertain as to make enterprise timid,\nand with the railroads and shippers\nengaged in a dispute over rates, the\nbusiness outlook is mixed, trade re\naction being very plain in some im\nportant directions, while at Ihe samn\nlime there are streaks of progress and\nactivity. It, is as a whole a waiting\nsituation with little to encourage\nspeculative enterprise until condi\ntions, now- doubtful or unsettled, be\ncome more clearly defined. An in\nteresting and In its possible outcome\nimportant development is the better\ndemand for bonds. This Is often an\naccompaniment of trade recession,\nbut It is also frequently the result\nof increased economies and therefore\nihe. forerunner of better limes. Trade\nadvices are of a mixed character. A\nnumber of the leading cities report .i\nmovement larger than a week ago.\nand good seasonable weather has\nbeen especially beneficial to retail\nbusiness. In dry goods conditions\nare relatively much better than in\nmost of Ihe other lylnes. In iron and\nsteel although there is considerable!\nactivity In the wire division the trade!\nI as a whole is much below full mill\n1 capacity and has suffered during the\nlast week by talk of price recession,\nbut this has met with official denials.\nThe deadlock over the bill of lading\ncontroversy continues, but money fa\neasy and the Bank of England with a\nhigh percentage of reserve maintains\nIts 3 per cent, rate of discount. The\nfeeling in banking and cotton clr\ndes is that Ihe controversy will final\nI y lie arranged.\nj By United Press Leased Special Wire.\nNEW A'ORK, Sept, 24.\u2014The weekly\nbank statement as issued to-day shows\nthe following changes:\nReserve on all deposits,\ndec. $4,638,000\nReserve on deposits other\nthan U. S., dec. $4,656,625\nLoans, Inc. 17,118,\u00bbOff\nSpools, dec. $3,424,500\nLegal tenders, dee. $790,800\nDeposits. Inc. $1,628,800\nCirculation, Inc. $1,149,600\nTotal loans. .$1.281,OsO.oou\nThe snrplnp Is $19,2.1...200, as com\nBank Maternent.\npared with $10.319,12.. Inst year, *nd\n$52,373,600 two years ago.\nj\n\nSEVERAL Bin'll'\nI> FIRE I> GARAGE\nBv Unltet Press Leased Sp\u00e9cial Wire.\nNEW ACRE, Se P t 24\u2014One man is j\nmissing and Is believed to have been i\n(burned to death; two were fatally!\nhurt, and a half dozen seriously in\nlured in a fire that destroyed Boyl\nI son's garage. 142 East Fortieth street,\nI to-day. The man supposed to he\nI dead was a Greek employe of Ihe\nestablishment.\nThirl' -one big touring car\u00bb were de\nhe explosion ot their\nthe entire\nslroyed and\n1 gasoline tanks aroused\nneighborhood and was responsible for\ninjuries to several people Jumping\n,,tnHrm\nfrom u<nd \u00b0*\"'_\ni\nj\nlx\u00ab\u00ab as..!. In Different Retiens Re\nI Two (\u00bbhock\u00bb In Plfterent Hegte, is He\nperted \u00ab1 the Kerne Time.\nBv Cnit el Press Leased Special B re.\nCLEVELAND, O., Sept. 24\u2014Father\nOdenbach of St. Ignatius College ob\naervatory to-day reports the selsmo\ni graph record of two simultaneous\nI earthquakes In different quarters of\ni the globe. He says If Is the first\nj time In his observation that such a\nI record has been made.\nEARTHttf .AKE REPORTS.\nBS\nGEOGRAPHERS\nVISIT THE CITY\nGo to Old Swedes Church and\nHave Luncheon at the\nHistorical Society\nNOT HERE TO EXPLORE\n\"FOLLY FIELD\" PARK\nSlxty-two members of the Philad*!\nphla Geographical Society are visiting\nWilmington to-day. The delegation\narrlved*on the Wilson Cine boat at\n11.15 this morning, and went at once\nto Old Swedes Church, where they\nwere the guests of Vicar and Mrs A\nE. Clay.\nThe committee in charge of the\ncursion are Miss M. J. Holmes, chair -1\nman. Miss E. E. Massey, acting chair\nman. Miss Rachel Barker and Hr. J\nB. F. Buckingham. The president of\nthe society, which numbers nearly one\nthousand members, is Henry G. Bry\nant, who was not on the excursion.\nThe seer\"\nA distin\ngnished member of Ihe society, who\nis In Wilmington to-day, js Captain\nBonsall. the last surviving member of\nthe Kane Polar expedition. Captain\nhe Is now- in Europe.\n|tary Is Dr. La Bon tel Her.\nBonsall is hale and hearty, and looks\nquite ready for another polar expedi\ntion.\nAfter Ihe party visited Old Swedes,\nthey went to the Delaware Historical\nSociety building and inspected the ex\nhibits\nAt 1.30 luncheon was served it\nHanqa's Cafe. In the afternoon the\nsociety will tnke the street ears ov<\nthe Washington street bridge, and\nvslk through Brandywine Park, ob\nserving the geographical features\nparticularly They will return to\nPhiladelphia by boat, late in the after\nnoon.\nMisses Rachel and Lou Barker,\nmembers of the excursion, will he en\ntertained over Sunday by Miss Mary\nS. Burr.\nIt is ten years since the Philadel\nphia Geographical Society has visited\nvisilej) Wilmington, and they are\nmuch pleased to have a pleasant day.\nand an auspicious beginning to the\ntrip.\nSome Wilmingtonlans to-day sug\ngested that the geographers fake ad\nvantage of the visit of the Geograph\nical Society to have an exploration of\n\"Folly Field.\" the new 120,000 play\nground out, in the western wilderness.\nWith an experienced Arctic explorer\nto guide the expedition, there ought to\nbe a good hope of having the unknown\ncountry charted and scientific da*a\ntaken concerning the fauna and flora,\nand wealth of the supposititious value\nof $20,000 burled in that land.\nLetter\u00bb on Estate\u00bb\nRcgiRtcr of wins 'walker today\ni Pl ,er 8 of administration on\nhp eBtaUs of j ohn O'Donnell to Frank\nSpeakman. and on estate of John\nArm P tronK Fannie and John G\n__\nM i\u00bbv P4Y COUNTY TAX\nJhcre was a m\u00bbh of country people\nW\nf N\u00ab\" Castle Chris b.na and Bran\nhundreds sal In tho Le \u00bby\nCourt room and were kept bus y. Th\nP\"OPj<* W* n w rr j' n ,OU8 to MKM,rP\n*he pcrjectl r( P iltc\n'rilVOUVRS A MASTIFF\nGIRL ON4JI I.KS A MASTIrr.\nAthletic Training of Value to MBs\nof Sixteen from New York.\nMONT I CELLO, N. Y\u201e Sept. 24\u2014As\na result of her training re\nreived at St. Mary's Garden City\nSchool, Miss Alma Mueller, sixteen,\nprobably saved lier life to-day by\ngrappling with an infuriated mastiff\nwhich had attacked her. Although\nbadly bitten In the fare her eondl\niion is not considered dangerous\nMiss Mueller, who Is Hie daught\"r\n0 f M r and Mrs. R. J. Mueller, of New\nfriends tn Liberty, and It was there\nencountered the dog. She was\nremoved to her home here and her\nYork and Monlicello, was visiting\np^ r \u201enls communicated with the\nPasteur Institution authorities, who\nj have taken charge of the patient. Tin\ndog was not mad.\nj\ni\nEVERYBODY TO\nEAT ROAST OX\nSI. Thomas' Church, has completed ar\nrangements for the barbecue to be\nheld on Wednesday evening next on\nthe campus of St. Thomas'Hall. There\nwill be music by a band and many\nThe Rev. John J. Connelly, pastor of\nother features\nGerman Irish and Italian Saengev\nbunds will sing in the course oftho\nevening. A large ox will be roasted\nand Ihe juicy meat will be served\nalong with other edibles.\nAmong the special guests of Father\nwjl bp th fo lowlnp: 8 ena\nR A duPont Con(\u00e7rPBSI 4 n Wll\nJtam H H eald. former Governor Prea\nton L, Pa> former Chancellor John R.\n\u00bbcjeholson, Attorney General A. C.\nGray. Mayor Spruance. City Solicitor\nJohn' W. Brady, I,. Irving Handy,\nj 0 hn S. Rossell. John J. Malloy Pre\u00bbt\nand members of City Connell,\nmember\u00bb of the Park Commission,\nboard of Health, Street and Sewer Di\nparlment, City Treasurer Ross. City\nAuditor Kurtz and representatives of\nthe press.\nSuspended Football Players For\nSwearing.\nELGIN. Ill.. Sept. 24\u2014Elgin's high\nschool football team is on a strike\nand refused to come out for practice\nbecause two of Ha members were sus\npended for swearing\nImite Dr. Cnrkran Bark.\nAt the quarterly Conference of\nUnion M. E. Church last night, pre\nj aided over by District Superintendent\n1 E, L. Hoffecker, the Rev. Dr. AV. V.\n1 Corkran was extended an Invitation to\nreturn as pastor for another year.\nHaving a Tag Day.\nSt. Paul's U. A. M. E. Church is\nhaving a tag day today.\nw _\nServices at Layton Home.\nThere will be services to-morrow all,\nday at the Layton Home, Thirty-fifth\nand Market streets. In charge of a\nband of missionaries from Phlladel\nphla Tag dav for the Layton Home\nWill be held October 29.\nBANK CLEARINGS.\nThe clearings of the Wilmington\nbanks for the week ending to-day\namounted to $1,556,431. For the cor\nresponding week of last year thoy\niimoimtrH to 81.393.073\nLearn While You Earn\nat the\n\ny\ne'\n\n\nOF GOLDEY COU1\u00c6GE\nBegins Nexl Monday. September 26\u20143 nights a week, 2 hours a\nnight\u20146 hours instruction a week and in one study if desired.\nBookkeeping\nArithmetic.\nRapid Calculations\nEnglish.\nTypewriting\nSpelling.\nDrafting.\nShorthand,\nPenmanship,\nThoroughly Taught by Expert Instructors\nSelect Studies You want. Individual Instruction. No Class R\u00e9ci\ntations. No Entrance Examinations. Bolli Sexes Attend. Positive\nly no Embarrassment Special Low Rales.\nYou Save $6 by Enrolling To-night.\nCall and talk it over with us.\nInstitute Building, Eighth and Market Sts.\n\n(First Floor)\nLearn While You Earn\nTROUBLE OVER\nINSURANCE\ne\nWilliam J.Keatlcy Enters Suit\nto Recover a Claim of\n$5,000 in Benefits\nIn the Superior court this morning\nJohn Biggs and Armor D. Chaytor, Jr.,\npresented a petition in Ihe ease of\nK eat ley vs. the Grand Fr.lerlnty.\n.._I\nThey asked for an order directing the\ndefendant to produce in Ihe offire of\nIhe Prothonatory for Inspection an ap\nplteatlon for Insurance and certificate\nof medical examination.\nAVII liant J. Keatly in .March\nj\n1909. j\ntook out an Insurance policy in the i\ncompany for $2.000 and In June, 1909, j\nlook ont another lor $3,000. He died\nin October 1909. The Grand Frater\n\u25a0H\nnlty refused to pay the face of Ihe pol\nleles. alleging that Keatley in his ap\nplication gave fraudulent and mislead\ning iniVIPl to s* of the cjues\nlions. Suit was entered for the rccov\nery of $6.000 and upon the application I\nof Leonard E. Wales Ihe case was\ntiansferred to the United Stales Cir\ncuit Court. Then the plaintiff with\ndrew the suit and commenced one In\nthe Superior court for $'2.000 and an\nother in the United States Circuit\nCourt for $3.000. The court made an\norder that\nTuesday- so that they can bo inspected\nThe case will be at issue at the No\nvember term of court.\nthe papers be filed on\nj\nj\ni\nPart 1 of Volume 1 of Boyce's stale\nreports has been issued. It was com- 1\npiled by Judge Boyce and Court Sien\nographer Hardesty. The volume covers\nthe cases heard from the appointment\nof Ihe new court up to the spring ses\nslons, 1910.\nLA IV REPORT\nMAKES ITS AI'PEARA\u00ceif E\nBOYCE'S\n\nDo You Want\nBeautiful Hair?\nHERE IS YOUR CHAN